{{Infobox protected area | name = Castle Rock State Park | iucn_category = III | photo = Castle Rock State Park 1.jpg | photo_caption = | map = Illinois | map_width = 225 | map_caption = Map of the [[U.S. state]] of [[Illinois]] showing the location of Castle Rock State Park | location = [[Ogle County, Illinois|Ogle County]], [[Illinois]], United States | nearest_city = [[Oregon, Illinois]] | coordinates = {{coords|41|58|08|N|89|22|55|W|display=inline, title}} | area = {{convert|2000|acre|0}} | established = 1921 | visitation_num = | visitation_year = | governing_body = [[Illinois Department of Natural Resources]] }}
'''Castle Rock State Park''' is an [[List of Illinois state parks|Illinois state park]] on {{convert|2000|acre|0}} in [[Ogle County, Illinois|Ogle County]], [[Illinois]], United States. A portion of the land was acquired by the "Friends of Our Native Landscape" in 1921.
[[Image:Castle Rock State Park 2.jpg|thumb|left|View of the [[Rock River (Mississippi River)|Rock River]] from Castle Rock.]]
==Geology== Castle Rock is a bluff of exposed [[St. Peter Sandstone]] from the Middle [[Ordovician]] period. Newly exposed sections are white [[quartz]], while older areas have browner tints from the formation of [[limonite]]. The bluff is along the axis of the [[Sandwich Fault Zone]], separating Ordovician exposures from those of the [[Cambrian]] period.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Wiggers|first=Ray|title=Geology Underfoot in Illinois|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cPfw7aIlowIC&pg=PA39|pp=39–41|accessdate=May 11, 2015}}</ref>
==2008 closing== Castle Rock State Park was one of eleven state parks slated to close indefinitely on November 1, 2008 due to budget cuts by former Illinois governor Rod Blagojevich.<ref name=close>Dempsey, Pam G. "[http://www.news-gazette.com/news/state_regional/2008/08/29/governor_closing_24_state_sites_including_kickapoo_state_park Governor closing 24 state sites, including Kickapoo State Park]", ''The News Gazette'' ([[Champaign, Illinois]]), August 29, 2008, accessed August 31, 2008.</ref> After delay, which restored funding for some of the parks, a proposal to close seven state parks and a dozen state historic sites, including Castle Rock, went ahead on November 30, 2008.<ref name=garcia>Garcia, Monique and Gregory, Ted. "[http://archives.chicagotribune.com/2008/nov/29/local/chi-state-parks_29nov29 State park closings a tough pill for some to swallow]", ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'', November 29, 2008, accessed April 12, 2009.</ref> After the impeachment of Illinois Governor Blagojevich, new governor Pat Quinn reopened the closed state parks in February.<ref name=idnropen>"[http://dnr.state.il.us/pubaffairs/2009/February/Parks_reopen.htm Governor Quinn calls on IDNR to Reopen State Parks] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090408080239/http://www.dnr.state.il.us/pubaffairs/2009/February/Parks_reopen.htm |date=2009-04-08 }}", ([[Press release]]), ''[[Illinois Department of Natural Resources]]'', February 26, 2009, accessed April 12, 2009.</ref> In March 2009 Quinn announced he is committed to reopening the state historic sites by June 30, 2009.<ref name=huffpo>"[http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2009/03/25/quinn-to-reopen-state-par_n_179227.html Quinn To Reopen State Parks And Historic Sites Closed By Blagojevich]", ''[[The Associated Press]]'', via ''[[Huffington Post]]'', March 25, 2009, accessed April 12, 2009.</ref>
