[[File:Esmeralda 3d hires.jpg|thumb|alt=|Esmeralda Bank]] {{Coordinate|article=/|NS=15.00|EW=145.25|type=mountain|dim=50000|region=MP|map=right|maptype=relief}}
'''Esmeralda Bank''' is a [[submarine volcano]] around 37 km west of [[Tinian|Tinian Island]] of the [[Northern Mariana Islands]] in the [[Pacific Ocean]]. It is located at the southern end of the [[Izu-Bonin-Mariana Arc|Mariana Arc]]. It has three summit cones lying along a north-south line. The highest peak is about 43 meters below the sea surface and has a caldera about 3 kilometers wide and several [[Parasitic cone|parasitic cones]] on the edge of the caldera. Sulfur boils and water discoloration have been observed at the site of the volcano, attributed to either eruptions or [[Fumarole|fumarolic]] activity.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://volcanoes.usgs.gov/volcanoes/esmeralda_bank/|title=USGS: Volcano Hazards Program NMI Esmeralda Bank|last=Program|first=Volcano Hazards|website=volcanoes.usgs.gov|access-date=2018-06-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://oceanexplorer.noaa.gov/explorations//04fire/background/marianaarc/media/esmeralda_vr.html|title=Mariana Volcanic Chain: Esmeralda Bank Volcano|website=oceanexplorer.noaa.gov|access-date=2018-06-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://scienceblogs.com/eruptions/2010/07/16/a-volcanic-cruise-through-the-1/|title=A volcanic cruise through the Mariana Islands: Part 2|work=Eruptions|access-date=2018-06-15|language=en-US}}</ref> == Last Known Activity == On May 26, 1987, a pilot observed violently bubbling and discolored water over Esmeralda Bank.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=|title=Global Volcanism Program {{!}} Report on Esmeralda Bank (United States) — August 1987|url=http://volcano.si.edu/showreport.cfm?doi=10.5479/si.GVP.SEAN198708-284210.|journal=|language=en|volume=|pages=|doi=10.5479/si.gvp.sean198708-284210|via=}}</ref>
== References == <references /> {{volcano-stub}} [[Category:Submarine volcanoes]] [[Category:Volcanoes]] [[Category:Volcanoes of the United States]]

{{lowercase}}

'''g Aquarii''' can refer to two different astronomical objects:

* '''g<sup>1</sup> Aquarii''' or [[66 Aquarii]],<ref>[http://vizier.u-strasbg.fr/viz-bin/VizieR-5?-out.add=.&-source=IV/27A/catalog&recno=3849 HD 215167], database record, HD-DM-GC-HR-HIP-Bayer-Flamsteed Cross Index, N. D. Kostjuk, Institute of Astronomy of Russian Academy of Sciences, 2002; [[Centre de Données astronomiques de Strasbourg|CDS]] ID [http://cdsarc.u-strasbg.fr/viz-bin/Cat?cat=IV%2F27A&target=readme IV/27A].</ref> commonly called simply '''g Aquarii'''.<ref>{{cite simbad | title=* g Aqr | accessdate=2014-05-01}}</ref>
* '''g<sup>2</sup> Aquarii''' or [[68 Aquarii]].<ref>[http://vizier.u-strasbg.fr/viz-bin/VizieR-5?-out.add=.&-source=IV/27A/catalog&recno=3858 HD 215721], database record, HD-DM-GC-HR-HIP-Bayer-Flamsteed Cross Index, N. D. Kostjuk, Institute of Astronomy of Russian Academy of Sciences, 2002; [[Centre de Données astronomiques de Strasbourg|CDS]] ID [http://cdsarc.u-strasbg.fr/viz-bin/Cat?cat=IV%2F27A&target=readme IV/27A].</ref>

