==C==

{{glossary}}
{{term|term= '''[[camouflage]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= An inconspicuous appearance adopted by an organism in order to deceive possible [[predator]]s or [[prey]].}}

{{term|term= '''[[canopy (biology)|canopy]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= }}

{{term|term= '''[[carbon cycle]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= The [[biogeochemical cycle]] by which [[carbon]] is exchanged between the [[biosphere]], [[pedosphere]], [[geosphere]], [[hydrosphere]], and earth's [[atmosphere]].}}

{{term|term= '''[[carrying capacity]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= The maximum number of individuals a given environment's [[resource (biology)|resources]] can support, including the food and water available for that environment.}}

{{term|term= '''[[charismatic megafauna]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= A large animal species with widespread popular appeal that [[environmental activist]]s use to achieve conservation goals well beyond just those species. Examples include the [[giant panda]], the [[Bengal tiger]], and the [[blue whale]]. Compare [[#flagship species|flagship species]].}}

{{term|term= '''[[chemical ecology]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= A branch of ecology which studies the use by organisms of naturally occurring chemical compounds, for example in defense against [[predator]]s.}}

{{term|term= '''[[climate]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= The long-term average weather pattern in a particular place.}}

{{term|term= '''[[climate change]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= Change in weather conditions such as [[cloud cover]], [[wind speed]], [[temperature]], [[rainfall]] or [[humidity]] in a specific region.}}

{{term|term= '''[[climate change and ecosystems]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= }}

{{term|term= '''[[climax community]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= A [[community (ecology)|community]] of [[plants]] and [[animals]] that has reached a stable state, occurring when the different species are best [[adaptation|adapted]] to average conditions in a given area.}}

{{term|term= '''[[colony (biology)|colony]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= }}

{{term|term= '''[[commensalism]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= A [[symbiotic]] relationship between two organisms of different species, in which one of the organisms benefits while the other remains unaffected.}}

<span id="community"></span>{{term|term= '''[[community (ecology)|community]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= An assemblage of various organisms living in the same environment.}}

<span id="community ecology"></span>{{term|term= '''[[community ecology]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= A branch of ecology which studies the interactions between species within an ecological [[community (ecology)|community]]. Also called ''synecology''.}}

<span id="competition"></span>{{term|term= '''[[competition]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= Organisms from the same or from different species competing with each other for food, living conditions,  [[reproduction|reproductive]] success, or any limited [[resource (biology)|resource]]; the most [[fitness (biology)|adapted individuals]] come out on top and thus survive and reproduce.}}

{{term|term= '''[[competitive exclusion principle]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= A [[biological rule]] which states that two species cannot coexist in the same environment if they are competing for exactly the same [[resource (biology)|resource]].}}

{{term|term= '''[[coniferous forest]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= One of the main terrestrial [[biome]]s, culminating in the [[taiga]].}}

{{term|term= '''[[conservation biology]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= The study of Earth's [[biodiversity]] which aims at protecting natural habitats and the plant and animal species living in them.}}

<span id="consumer"></span>{{term|term= '''[[consumer (food chain)|consumer]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= An organism, usually an animal, that feeds on plants or other animals. Compare [[#heterotroph|heterotroph]].}}

{{term|term= '''[[cooperation]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= The process by which organisms work together for mutual benefit.}}

{{term|term= '''[[coral reef]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= }}

{{term|term= '''[[courtship display]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= Ritual social behavior between possible mates.}}

{{term|term= '''[[cryosphere]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= The combined portions of Earth's surface where water is in [[solid]] form as [[ice]], including [[sea ice]], lake ice, river ice, [[snow]], [[glacier]]s, [[#ice cap|ice caps]], [[ice sheet]]s, and frozen ground such as [[#permafrost|permafrost]]. There is significant overlap with the [[#hydrosphere|hydrosphere]].}}

{{glossary end}}
